==Production==
{{Rquote|right|''Mad Dogs'' has got much more of a filmic quality to it. In a way, it doesn't feel as if we're making television.|[[Philip Glenister]] describing the style of the series.<ref name=simmguardian/>}}
The idea behind ''Mad Dogs'' came from the friendship between the four main actors, who wanted to work together for a television project, as well as Cris Cole and executive producer Suzanne Mackie.<ref name=pressrelease/> The four initially wanted to make a story about a [[rock band]], but decided that making programmes about bands have been "done to death."<ref name=beesleyintv/> To write the series, Cole was influenced by the works of [[David Lynch]] and the [[Coen brothers]] as inspiration to the kind of storytelling that is "never quite what you think it is going to be."<ref name=pressrelease/>

The series initially gained interest from major terrestrial networks such as the [[BBC]] and [[ITV]]. However, Max Beesley and Philip Glenister grew frustrated with the comments from the commissioning teams from the networks. Glenister stated "the problem with the BBC and ITV is more people coming in and telling you what to do. We are grown up and big enough to know where the boundaries are." They ultimately settled for [[British Sky Broadcasting|Sky]], as the network was "the one that we believed would let us do what we wanted."<ref name=guardian2>{{cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2010/aug/03/mad-dogs-turned-down-bbc-itv?INTCMP=SRCH |title=Mad Dogs stars: we turned down BBC and ITV |first=Mark |last=Sweeney |date=3 August 2010 |accessdate=20 February 2011 |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]}}</ref> Later in January 2012, Glenister believed their decision to go with Sky was "vindicated," as the terrestrial networks would restrict its content, violence and language. The actor further stated that the restrictions would not make the series "the show it is and it wouldn't be the show we wanted to make."<ref name=simmguardian>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2012/jan/22/john-simm-interview-mad-dogs?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487 |title=John Simm interview: 'I don't really do awards' |first=Gareth |last=McLean |date=22 January 2012 |accessdate=7 February 2012 |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]}}</ref> Head of Sky Drama Elaine Pyke had an immediate interest in the project, as she was "immediately grabbed by how thrilling, scary and funny it is," believing it to be "the perfect show for Sky1."<ref name=pressrelease>{{cite web |url=http://www.atvnewsnetwork.co.uk/today/index.php/atv-today/2868-mad-dogs-for-sky-one |title=Mad Dogs for Sky One |first=Dominic |last=Knight |work=AVT Today |date=5 May 2010 |accessdate=5 March 2011}}</ref> In a separate interview, Beesley stated "Andy [Harries] basically put the show out to a few of the networks and Sky said 'Bang! Here's the money, go and make it and we'll give you notes later on, but really do have the freedom to make it,' which is great, and there's not a lot of that happens nowadays."<ref name=beesleyintv>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/tubetalk/a302032/max-beesley-talks-mad-dogs.html |title=Max Beesley talks 'Mad Dogs' |first=Alex |last=Fletcher |date=7 February 2011 |accessdate=5 March 2011 |work=[[Digital Spy]]; Tube Talk}}</ref>

[[File:PortalsVells-Calvi<U+00E0>-Mallorca-rafax.JPG|thumb|left|The series was filmed on location in Mallorca.]]
''Mad Dogs'' was commissioned as a four-part series by Pyke, with the official announcement made in May 2010. Cole wrote the episodes. It was produced by [[Left Bank Pictures]], the same production company responsible for other series including [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Wallander (British TV series)|Wallander]]'' and Sky1's ''[[Strike Back (TV series)|Strike Back]]''.<ref name=guardian1>{{cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2010/may/05/john-simm-philip-glenister-mad-dogs?INTCMP=SRCH |title=John Simm and Philip Glenister to star in Sky1's Mad Dogs |first=Jason |last=Deans |date=5 May 2010 |accessdate=20 February 2011 |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]}}</ref> It continues Sky's commitment to investing in new dramas with all-star casts.<ref name=digspy1/> The series sees the return of John Simm and Philip Glenister, who previously worked together on the BBC One series ''[[Life on Mars (TV series)|Life on Mars]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a218259/simm-glenister-team-up-for-sky1-show.html |title=Simm, Glenister team up for Sky1 show |first=Catriona |last=Wightman |date=5 May 2010 |accessdate=20 February 2011 |work=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref> A casting note once went awry when "Tony Blair" (the armed man in a Tony Blair mask) was misspelled as "Tiny Blair"; as a result six [[Dwarfism|dwarf]]s auditioned for the part, and one of them ended up being cast in the role.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/mediamonkeyblog/2010/aug/29/andy-harries?INTCMP=SRCH |title=Andy Harries's media gossip |date=29 August 2010 |accessdate=20 February 2011 |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]}}</ref> Filming began in May 2010, and took place on location in Majorca,<ref name=guardian1/> over a period of 44 days.<ref name=palmapictures/> The series was budgeted at an estimated four million [[euro]]s, with a further <U+20AC>150,000 grant from the Mallorcan Tourism Foundation, who hoped the series would promote Majorca, and was co-produced by Palma Pictures.<ref name=majorca>{{cite web |url=http://www.seemallorca.com/news-events-and-what-s-on/news/mad-dogs-in-mallorca.html |title=Mad Dogs in Mallorca |first=Gavin |last=Carver |date=31 January 2011 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |work=See Mallorca}}</ref> In one scene, Glenister refused to go nude to shoot the four running to a [[swimming pool]], citing his age.<ref name=digspy2/> Half the filming crew were locals. Beesley noted that the Spanish crew were "fantastic," and joked the cast and British crew were given some half-days because of local involvement.<ref name=beesleyintv/>

Plans were underway for a second series as early as January 2011.<ref name=majorca/> Citing ratings success for the first series, Sky officially renewed ''Mad Dogs'' for a second of four episodes, which would also be written by Cris Cole. Beesley, Glenister, Simm and Warren would reprise their roles, with filming taking place over Summer 2011, and broadcast in January 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sky1.sky.com/mad-dogs-3/mad-dogs-2-confirmed-for-early-2012 |title=Mad Dogs Series 2 Commissioned For Early 2012 |accessdate=11 May 2011 |work=sky1.sky.com |publisher=[[British Sky Broadcasting]]}}</ref> Sometime after the second series finished filming in August 2011, Sky commissioned a third series, which will begin filming in January 2012.<ref name="test">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a354156/philip-glenister-mad-dogs-filming-third-series-from-january.html |title=Philip Glenister: 'Mad Dogs filming third series from January' |first=Paul |last=Millar |date=2 December 2011 |accessdate=2 December 2011 |publisher=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref> There were also talks of a spin off series, ''Mad Cats'', featuring a female cast. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/commissioning/sky-1s-mad-dogs-to-become-cats/5034976.article |title=Sky 1's Mad Dogs to become cast |date=24 November 2011 |accessdate=24 November 2011 |first=Jake |last=Kanter |work=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]] |publisher=[[Emap]]}}</ref> A final two-part fourth series was commissioned in January 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2013/01/sky-announces-2013-drama-slate-orders-final-season-of-mad-dogs-ian-fleming-mini-series-more/ |title=Sky Announces 2013 Drama Slate: Orders Final Season of 'Mad Men', Ian Fleming Mini-Series & More |first=Patrick |last=Munn |date=17 January 2013 |accessdate=25 February 2013 |publisher=TV Wise}}</ref>

==Promotion==
[[File:DavidLaChapelle1SecondFilm.jpg|thumb|Photographer David LaChapelle directed three 30-second advertisements for the series.]]
Three 30-second films were produced to be used as on-air promotions for the programme on all Sky channels and selected third-party channels. The promotions starred the cast, directed by [[David LaChapelle]] and shot on location in Majorca. Print, outdoor and online promotions were also made. Executive creative director Clare McDonald was impressed by LaChapelle's work because the adverts were "staying true to our vision." Television promotions were first broadcast on Sky1 on 11 January 2011.<ref name=digspy1>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/broadcasting/news/a297412/lachapelle-creates-sky1-mad-dogs-promo.html |title=LaChapelle creates Sky1 'Mad Dogs' promo |first=Andrew |last=Laughlin |date=12 January 2011 |accessdate=11 February 2011 |work=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref> On 28 January, a preview of the first two episode were screened at the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] (BAFTA) event in [[London]]. This was followed by a questions and answers session by Marc Warren, Cris Cole, Suzanne Mackie and Adrian Shergold.<ref name=palmapictures>{{cite web |url=http://www.palmapictures.es/html/news/2011/01/31/mad-dogs-sky-one-mallorca/ |title=Mad Dogs, Sky One, Mallorca |date=31 January 2011 |accessdate=5 March 2011 |work=Palma Pictures}}</ref>

==Release and reception==

===Broadcast and ratings===
Scheduling of the series has been changed over the course of its development. The first announcement of the series in May 2010 stated it would be broadcast during the spring 2011,<ref name=guardian1/> but by August it was announced it would be moved up to the autumn schedule,<ref name=guardian2/> before it was ultimately settled to broadcast in February 2011. The series premiere received overnight ratings of 967,000 viewers and a 4 per cent audience share. It became the second largest multichannel audience of the night, behind a repeat of ''[[EastEnders]]'' on [[BBC Three]], which was seen by 1.061 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2011/feb/11/tv-ratings-mad-dogs |title=Mad Dogs grabs 967,000 viewers |first=Josh |last=Halliday |date=11 February 2011 |accessdate=11 February 2011 |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]}}</ref> The consolidated ratings for the first episode raised to 1.61 million viewers, which made the episode the second largest multichannel audience in its week, behind an episode of ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' on [[E4 (channel)|E4]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barb.co.uk/viewing/weekly-top-30? |title=Weekly Top 30 Programmes (See week Feb 07-Feb 13, 2011 and scroll down to Others) |work=BARB.co.uk |publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]] |accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> It also became the 17th highest rated programme ever for Sky1.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leftbankpictures.co.uk/latest-news/mad-dogs-first-episode-ranks-11th-highest-rated-programme-ever-on-sky-1.html |title=Mad Dogs' first episode ranks 17th highest rated programme ever on Sky 1 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |work=[[Left Bank Pictures]]}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Overnight ratings declined steadily to 802,000 by episode two,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a304535/celebrity-juice-bursts-past-1m.html |title='Celebrity Juice' bursts past 1m |first=Andrew |last=Laughlin |date=18 February 2011 |accessdate=19 February 2011 |work=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref> and 691,000 by episode three.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s127/masterchef/news/a305856/itvs-marchlands-fends-off-masterchef.html |title=ITV's 'Marchlands' fends off 'MasterChef' |first=Andrew |last=Laughlin |date=25 February 2011 |accessdate=26 February 2011 |work=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref> The first series finale went up to 938,000 viewers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a307153/marchlands-concludes-with-59m.html |title='Marchlands' concludes with 5.9m |first=Andrew |last=Laughlin |date=4 March 2011 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |work=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref> The second series premiered on [[Sky1]] on 19 January 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a356877/mad-dogs-series-two-air-date-confirmed-first-trailer-unveiled.html |title='Mad Dogs' series two air date confirmed, first trailer unveiled |first=Paul |last=Millar |date=20 December 2011 |accessdate=28 December 2011 |publisher=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref>

===Critical reception===
Michael Deacon of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reacted positively towards the series, stating "episode one was enjoyably sinister. It was also, once or twice, quite amusing, in (of course) a blokey way." Deacon liked the beginning of the pilot where the main characters record a video message, stating "this is what Mad Dogs did well <U+2013> like any competent suspense thriller, it made you ask questions throughout. The episode bubbled with foreboding, right up to the cliffhanger." Deacon also noted at the cliffhanger that "the most disturbing sight wasn't the shower of blood but the gunman's rubber mask, which was of a grinning Tony Blair."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/michael-deacon/8317167/Philip-Glenister-in-Mad-Dogs-Sky1-review.html |title=Philip Glenister in Mad Dogs, Sky1, review |first=Michael |last=Deacon |date=11 February 2011 |accessdate=11 February 2011 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=Telegraph Media Group}}</ref> John Crace of ''[[The Guardian]]'' however, was more mixed, starting "after unsuccessfully fobbing us off with endless series of Ross Kemp looking macho, Sky is now throwing serious money at getting viewers to watch something other than sport." Crace was critical of the set up of the episode, stating "I'm all for allowing a drama time to breathe but we didn't really need a whole hour just to establish that Alvo was a bit dodgy and that the four others had complications in their lives. Rather than building menace, the snail-like pace dissipated it," However, he reacted positively towards the end, as "things did eventually look up," adding "there's hope for Mad Dogs yet."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2011/feb/11/tv-review-mad-dogs |title=TV review: Mad Dogs, 30 Rock and The Culture Show |first=John |last=Crace |date=11 February 2011 |accessdate=11 February 2011 |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]}}</ref>

Jane Simon of the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' believed the "setting and the gangsterish plot are both reminiscent of that great British movie ''[[Sexy Beast]]'', and this first instalment of the four part series presses all the right buttons," adding "it has naturalistic performances, an <U+00AD>effortless blend of comedy and sinister undertones plus rather more shots of Marc Warren's bum cheeks than might be considered absolutely necessary."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/columnists/todays-tv/2011/02/10/mad-dogs-sky1-9pm-115875-22910974/ |title=Mad Dogs - Sky1, 9pm |first=Jane |last=Simon |date=10 February 2011 |accessdate=5 March 2011 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]}}</ref> Ben Walsh of ''[[The Independent]]'' rated the series three stars out of five, having written "there's far too much exposition, a very daft plot, some risible dialogue and yet Sky's ripe four-parter is horribly compelling," and added "it's extremely silly, but Simm and Glenister are always compelling and they make this gamey tale of gangsters, police corruption and 'friendship' work."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/dvd-mad-dogs-15-2231470.html |title=DVD: Mad Dogs (15) |first=Ben |last=Walsh |date=4 March 2011 |accessdate=5 March 2011 |work=[[The Independent]] |publisher=Independent Print Limited}}</ref> Reviewing the first two episode, ''[[The Stage]]'' believed the first was "a slow-burning exploration" and "all very intriguing and disturbing, with a great performance by Chaplin as the smilingly psychotic host." However, the reviewer criticised the death of Alvo, as he was considered the most "compelling character" and since "sent the plot line spinning off into less original territory," adding the producers took ideas from crime capers such as ''Sexy Beast'' and ''[[Shallow Grave]]''. However, the reviewer added "what ''Mad Dogs'' lacks in originality it makes up for in energy, verve and humour. The dialogue positively crackles with great lines." In the end, the reviewer stated that ''Mad Dogs'' "may be an unapologetic crowd pleaser, but it is a finely made one, with excellent performances from a dream cast. It also offers the only opportunity I have of seeing blue skies, azure waters and sunshine in February, so I am in for the duration."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/31334/tv-review |title=TV review: Mad Dogs, Sky 1, Thursday 10 February, 9pm |date=18 February 2011 |accessdate=5 March 2011 |work=[[The Stage]] |publisher=The Stage Newspaper Limited}}</ref>

Ryan Lambie of ''Den of Geek'' said of the first episode; "In terms of writing and acting, ''Mad Dogs'' is good, but not perfect, and much of its knock-about banter is uncannily like any Brit gangster flick you've ever seen," like "''Sexy Beast: the series''." However Lambie noted "when events push its premise from naff lads' drama into exotic thriller, ''Mad Dogs'' gets infinitely better, and if nothing else, it keeps you guessing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denofgeek.com/television/767770/mad_dogs_episode_1_review.html |title=Mad Dogs episode 1 review |first=Ryan |last=Lambie |date=11 February 2011 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |work=Den of Geek}}</ref> As the series progressed, Lambie noted that ''Mad Dogs'' was "developing into a nifty TV thriller with an engaging sense of the absurd. Writer, Cris Cole, enjoys picking holes in his characters' machismo as the tension mounts, and the strange billboard posters dotted all over the sun-scorched island, which say "Yenda a ninguna parte," ("Going nowhere") are perhaps a foreshadowing of their imminent fate."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denofgeek.com/television/776367/mad_dogs_episode_2_review.html |title=Mad Dogs episode 2 review |first=Ryan |last=Lambie |date=17 February 2011 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |work=Den of Geek}}</ref> However, Lambie was disappointed at the ending for being "unexpectedly flat," adding "the major plot twist that the previous three-or-so hours appeared to allude to never arrives, [...] I couldn't help but feel that, as the closing credits rolled on the whole saga, the tension and intrigue that had gradually built up in previous weeks had been allowed to slip away.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denofgeek.com/television/795485/mad_dogs_episode_4_review_series_finale.html |title=Mad Dogs episode 4 review: series finale |first=Ryan |last=Lambie |date=3 March 2011 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |work=Den of Geek}}</ref>

===Home media release===
The first series of ''Mad Dogs'' was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc]] in the United Kingdom on 7 March 2011.<ref name=series1dvd>{{cite web |url=http://www.bva.org.uk/node/1529305 |title=Mad Dogs |publisher=British Video Association |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref> The second series was released on DVD in the UK on 12 March 2012,<ref name=series2dvd>{{cite web |url=http://www.bva.org.uk/node/1798392 |title=Mad Dogs: Series 2 |publisher=British Video Association |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref> along with a collectors boxset containing both series.<ref name=series12dvd>{{cite web |url=http://www.bva.org.uk/node/1798394 |title=Mad Dogs: Series 1 and 2 |publisher=British Video Association |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref> All sets are released with a "15" [[British Board of Film Classification]] (BBFC) certificate (indicating it is unsuitable for viewers under the age of 15 years old).<ref name=series1dvd/><ref name=series2dvd/><ref name=series12dvd/>

===Award nominations===
''Mad Dogs'' was nominated for the British Academy Television Award for Best Serial Drama at the [[British Academy Television Awards 2011|2011 ceremony]] but lost out to the [[Channel 4]] series ''[[Any Human Heart (TV series)|Any Human Heart]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/television/winners-nominees-2011,1766,BA.html#jump5 |title=Television Awards Nominees and Winners in 2011 |date=26 April 2011 |accessdate=26 May 2011 |work=bafta.org}}</ref> In 2012 it was nominated for a [[Broadcast (magazine)|''Broadcast'' Award]] for Best Drama Series or Serial, but lost to the [[ITV1]] period drama ''[[Downton Abbey]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a363715/broadcast-awards-2012-winners-in-full.html |title=Broadcast Awards 2012: Winners in full |first=Catriona |last=Wightman |date=3 February 2012 |accessdate=3 February 2012 |work=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref>

